      <!-- WKD Delegation Explained -->
      <div class="mt-5 rounded-xl border border-green/20 bg-green/5 p-5">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-text">Web Key Directory (WKD) Delegation</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-muted">
          Leter.net is currently delegating OpenPGP public key discovery to the global
          <a class="text-green underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-green/80 transition-colors" href="https://keys.openpgp.org" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">keys.openpgp.org</a> directory.
          This is achieved via a <code class="rounded border border-white/10 bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-xs text-green">CNAME</code> DNS record pointing <code class="rounded border border-white/10 bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-xs text-green">openpgpkey.leter.net</code> to <code class="rounded border border-white/10 bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-xs text-green">wkd.keys.openpgp.org</code>.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-muted">
          <span class="font-medium text-text">Why we are doing this:</span> While Leter operates on a zero-knowledge architecture, true end-to-end encryption (E2EE) requires sender-side encryption. We are currently developing a sophisticated, automated internal WKD system to seamlessly push keys directly to our sovereign infrastructure. Until that system is officially published, delegating to the open standard public directory ensures external senders (using Thunderbid, Proton, etc.) can still easily and automatically fetch our users' keys.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-muted">
          <span class="font-medium text-text">Managing your keys:</span> Domain users must manually generate and upload their OpenPGP public key to <code class="rounded border border-white/10 bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-xs text-green">keys.openpgp.org</code>. The service will verify your <code class="rounded border border-white/10 bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-xs text-green">@leter.net</code> email address before making the key discoverable. You can delete or manage your published key at any time using their management portal.
        </p>
